text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%0a!Absence of Common Consonants Comparing English and Hawaiian%0a%0a:Author: Kushal_D%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHawaiian has an absence of fricatives unlike English%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aConsonants all have an associated manner of articulation, which is how the mouth is configured when making a particular sound. When a language uses all common manners of articulation, it means that there exist words in that language using each of the different consonant sounds. On the other hand, some languages do not use certain consonants - for example, languages with no fricatives do not use sounds that require restricting airflow through the oral cavity, like [f] or [θ]. %0a%0aTwo languages that differ in this regard are English and Hawaiian. English uses all of the common manners of articulation when it comes to producing consonants. However, unlike English, Hawaiian has no fricatives consonants. %0a%0aI found this interesting, mostly because Hawaii is a state of the USA now and so likely has had English emerge as a common language here. I would have assumed that the lack of a sound that is commonly used in English would have proved to be a barrier to learning the language. However, based on a document released by the Hawaiian government on their non-English speaking population, this does not seem to be the case - only 0.6325%25 of their population does not speak English. Although newer generations learning English from when they're young and immigrants might heavily affect this, it might also mean that a difference in the set of consonants used might not be a large barrier to learning a language like I initially assumed. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://wals.info/feature/18A#2/54.8/152.8%0ahttps://phoible.org/inventories/view/43%0ahttps://files.hawaii.gov/dbedt/economic/data_reports/Non_English_Speaking_Population_in_Hawaii_April_2016.pdf%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210223-185329-676370#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!/w/ and /v/ in Hawaiian  %0a-> - bellar%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aHawaiian does not use fricative consonants but includes /w/, which sounds kind of in between the /w/ and /v/ sounds in English. Foreigners to Hawaii sometimes mistake the /w/ sound as /v/. The Hawaiian /w/ is a bilabial consonant so it can be pronounced with lips barely touching or more voiced with more lip contact. But because the teeth are not involved the v ends up sounding softer, like the w sound. According to the article, any words with the v sound in Hawaiian have been derived from foreign languages. %0a%0aSource: http://www.ulukau.org/elib/cgi-bin/library?e=d-0voicesofeden-000Sec--11en-50-20-contact-book--1-010escapewin&a=d&d=D0.9&toc=0%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210223-185329-676370#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)
time=1614106409
