diff:1614106409:1613871861:=54,65c54%0a%3c #foxbegin 210223-185329-676370#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!/w/ and /v/ in Hawaiian  %0a%3c -> - bellar%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Hawaiian does not use fricative consonants but includes /w/, which sounds kind of in between the /w/ and /v/ sounds in English. Foreigners to Hawaii sometimes mistake the /w/ sound as /v/. The Hawaiian /w/ is a bilabial consonant so it can be pronounced with lips barely touching or more voiced with more lip contact. But because the teeth are not involved the v ends up sounding softer, like the w sound. According to the article, any words with the v sound in Hawaiian have been derived from foreign languages. %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: http://www.ulukau.org/elib/cgi-bin/library?e=d-0voicesofeden-000Sec--11en-50-20-contact-book--1-010escapewin&a=d&d=D0.9&toc=0%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210223-185329-676370#%0a---%0a> %0a
